f pain\nwhenever a similar missile came in\ncontact with his own cranium.\nThere wasn't much sldhping to be\ndone after these war cries began, and\nthe oldest inhabitants, realizing \"they\nwould he called on to tell when the\nlast snow fell and when the worst rfnow\nfell and all about all the previous\nsnows that evev fell, got up and began\nracking their brain.\n1\nI\nt\nr'J\nIF\n4\nTwo Previous Snows.\nif the dates given by all the oldest\ninhabitaats are accepted as correct,\nanow must have fallen every year in\nHattiesburg up to 1906. Yet all the\noldest inhabitants agree there have\nbeeu only two previous snows that lay\non the ground, the trouble being that\nthe most accurate of the city's men^giT\nhistorian's disagree on the dates.-\nAccording to the most generally ac\ncepted recollections, the last snow fell\nin 1996. Some say this was as far\nback as 1994 and some split the dif\nference and call it 1905. It really\nwasn't enough of a snow to be worth\nremembering, for the ground had been\nwet with rain a few hours before and\nthe snow didn't lay long enough to\nmake snow balls. And it has been\ndemonstrated today that the chief at\ntraction of snow to Hattjgsburglans is\n\u25a0now balls.\nThe real snow, it is generally ad\nmitted, was something like fourteen or\nf ^fifteen years ago. Most people remem\nf ber It because It came about the time\nof the Spanlsh-American war, and the\ndate most generally accepted is Feb\nruary 19, 1899. It is Bald that eight\ninches of saow ^Iay on the ground for\nseveral days.\nThe snow the older residents love\nt\n\nA\n\nto talk about, however, came thirty\ntwo years ago. While there was only\n^Ibout tljree inches of it, a drizzle and\nfreeze\nwalking\nfarmers\nimmediately following rendered\nceedtngly difficult and the\npent a good deal of their\ntime palling cattle out of the ponds,\nwhere th\nr.\nhad slipped on the ice.\ni\nToday's) snow turned to slush very\ne flakes were large, but\nnot firm aind contained more moisture\nthan thoHcfe which usually fail farther\nnorth, n\nquickly.\nY6 APPEAL IN\nLANE a BOWLER CASE.\nAT'\n\u2022t n\njlaeys for the City\nof Hat\nerday gave notice of an\nI State Supreme Court of\nLane Bowler vs. The\n\u00bbIch was sometime ago decld\nf lanceilor J. Morgan Stevens\nr to the city, and in which\nLmtiffs were given a judgment\n$7,699.\n'\u00abht\n\u00d6\nMeridian, Laurel, Natchez And Other\nCities Vlaited With Heaviest 8 now\nIn Many Years.\nMELTS AS IT FALLS IN\nMARDI GRAS CITY.\n(By Associated Press.)\nNew Orleans, Feb. 25.\u2014 Snow began\nfalling early here and although the\ntemperature stayed around thirty-two,\nit melted rapidly as it struck the\nground. Large portions of Mississip\npi and Louisiana reported deep snow\nfalls during the morning.\nSIX INCHES AT LAUREL.\nIt I\n(By Associated Press\nLaurel, Miss.. Feb. 25.\u2014Snow six\nj inches deep covere Laurel today,\nIs the heaviest snow in fifteen years\nj and many persons who never before\ni saw a snow are taking a holiday,\nVERY LIGHT AT NATCHEZ.\n(By Associated Press.)\nNatchez, Miss., Feb. 25 .\u2014A very\nlight snow, not enough to stay on the\nground long but sufficient to bring\npeople out of their beds early, fell here\nduring the early morning.\nTHREE INCHES AT MERIDIAN.\n(By Associated Press.)\nMeridian. Miss., Feb. 25.\u2014Three\ninches of snow fell here during the\nearly morning. It stayed on the\nground a few hours, but began to melt\nrapidly toward midday.\nHAIL AND SLEET INSTEAD OF\nSNOW ON THE GULF COAST.\n(By Associated Press.)\nGulfport, Miss., Feb. 25.\u2014The ther\nmometer went far below the freezing\npoint her last night and remained so\nthrough the morning. It is the cold\nest we ather the Gulf coast has experi\nenced in many years. A storm of hail\nan( j s ip e t accompanied the cold wave,\n\u00bbvj Q snow has fallen yet.\nto\nis\nor\nLegislature To\nAdjournMar. 14;\nPass Liquor Bill\nSENATE SUBSTITUTE, LES 8 STRIN\nGENT THAN ORIGINAL BILL,\nACCEPTED.\nSpecial to The News.\nJackson, Miss., Feb. 26.\u2014The lower\nhouse this afternon adopted a resolu\ntion reported from the steering com\nmittee providing for a sine die ad\njournment of the Mississippi Legisla\nture on March 14th. The resolution\nnow goes to the Senate, where there\nare indications that it will be adopted\nwithout a fight.\nThe lower house this afternoon\npassed the Senate substitute for the\nMay-Mott-Lewis anti-liquor bill by a\nvote of 83 to 21. The amendment is\nnot to the liking of the supporters of\nthe original bill, as it is considerably\nmilder in its restrictions. It was ac\ncepted, however, because House lead\ners learned that the Senate would not\nagree to any more stringent measure.\nSome of the House leaders went so\nfar aa to say the Senate bill is practi\ncally worthless.\nan\nof\nAEROPLANE AMBULANCES.\n\nLondon, Feb. 25.\u2014The British War\nOffice has decided to experiment with\n\"aeroplane ambulances\" to ascertain\nthe practibtlity of using air craft to\ntransport wounded from field of bat\n\nYoung Prima Donna\n\nI\n\n\nIl\n\nP\nMiss Lyne, who has just returned to\nthis country from a round-the-world j\nopera tour, is probably the youngest.\nprima donna now on the operatic\nstage. She is only twenty-two and j\nshe has been singing in public for the i\nIt I past two years. Her debut was made\nin London and she was hall id as the\nmost promising soprano since Patti.\nMiss Lyne hails from Allentown, Pa.\nSNOW-BALLING ENDS\nIN STREET FIGHT\nPHILIP ROLLS STRIKES DR. F. W.\nQUEEN, KNOCKING HIM\nTO GROUND.\nASSAULT CHARGE IS LODGED\nAttack Resented by Aged Optician\u2014\nEncounter Results in Disbanding of\nCrowd Which Had Spent Day Pelt\ning Everyone Who Passed.\nso\nThe jollification this morning over\nthe snow, in one instance resulted in\na difficulty in which Dr. F. W. Queen\nand Philip Rolls were involved and as\na result of which an affidavit, charg\ning assault and battery was lodged in\nthe City Court against Rolls. Hearing\nwill come up tomorrow morning.\nIt apears that Dr. Queen was pass\ning near where a large number of\nboys and men had congregated for the\npurpose of snow-balling everyone who\nchanced to pass,\ntook the assaults good-naturedly, and\nthe crowd pelted everyone, irrespec\ntive of age or sex.\nWhen Dr. Queen came down the\nstreet, someone in the crowd struck\nhim in the face with a snowball,\nwhich broke his glasses and cut his\nface. He was angered and showed re\nsentment by starting toward the\ncrowd expressing his displeasure. Be\nlieving that it was Rolls who had hit\nhim. Dr. Queen is said to have ap\nproached him and used an epithet,\nwhich Rolls resented with a blow\nfrom his fist, sending the doctor\nsprawling in the gutter, his face bleed\ning.\nMost pedestrians\nad\nthe\na\nis\nof\nac\nnot\nso\nRolls was arrested by a policeman\nand at once released upon his recog\nnizance.\nWhen seen by a newspaper represen\ntative, Dr. Queen was greatly ag\ngrieved and claimed that his resent\nment grew out of the fact that Rolls\nand another man had both hit him in\nthe face, bruising it and breaking his\nglasses.\nPhilip Rolls does not deny that he\nwas in the crowd aa one of the \u00abnow\nbailers, but does deny that he threw\nthe snowball of which Dr. Queen com\nplains, and further denies that he hit\nhim with a snowball at all.\ntie. According to semi-official au\nnouncement the military authorities\nwill place an aeroplane at the disposal\nof the British Red Cross Society for\nto the purpose of a demonstration of the\nbat- new method.\n\u2022tew- j be i\nMOTORMAN CHARGES TWO YOUNG\nMEN AT NORMAL ROBBED\nHIM OF $10.\nNO CLASSES TODAY AT COLLEGE\nOfficials of Institution Stand Behind\nAccused Boys and Claim They Will\nProve Alibi\u2014Traction Company Will\nNot Proaecute Caae.\nM. L. Norman, a motorman on the\nHardy Street car line, reported last\nnight upon his return from the last\nj\nrun at 11 o'clock, that he was held up\nand robbed immediately after he\nj reached the Normal\ni\nNormal C liege, who went out on his\nCollege, and al\nleges he recognized the parties who\nrobbed him as two students at the\nten o'clock run.\nNorman states that on his last run\nhe carried no passengers and upon\nreaching the college station, two men,\nthe lower part of their faces covered\nwith colored handkerchiefs, pointed\ntheir pistols in his face and demanded\nthat he give up his money.\nWhile one of the men kept his gun\non him, Norman says the other took\nfrom him his change pouch, which\ncontained about $10, relieved him of\nhis watch, which was afterwards\nturned and then searched his trouB\ners pockets, failing, however, to dis\ncover beneath a large bath of trans\nfer tickets a pocket hook containing\n$76 of personal funds.\nAs soon as the hold-up was report\ned to the sheriff, Deputy T. A. Cahal\nand others accompanied the motor\nman to the scene of the reported rob\nbery, and at the Normal College, Nor\nman pointed out the two young men\nwhom he accuses.\nGreat excitement resulted from the\nvisit of the officer and motorman to\nthe college, and it is strongly asserted\nby officers' and others at the college\nthat the fixing of the blame upon the\nyoung men whom Norman accuses, is\nclearly a case of mistaken identity.\nClasses have been suspended for the\nre\nday.\nThe mangement of the Hattiesburg\nTraction Company have not made any\naffidavit and disclaim any intention\nof prosecuting the case, in the absence\nof any other proof than the identifica\ntion by the motorman.\nIn the absence of the making of any\naffidavit and in face of the denial of\nthe college authorities that the ac\ncused young men are in anyway con\nnected with the alleged robbery, their\nnames are withheld from publication.\n8 UPREME COURT TO TAKE\nUP 80UTH MI 8 S. CASE 8\nThe clerk of the Supreme Court has\ngiven notice that the docket for the\nSouthern District of Mississippi will\nbe taken up the first week in June.\nA number of important cases Involv\ning- Hattiesburg people are to be dealt\nwith.\nin\nFrank Denied Hearing\nAppeal For New Ttial\n(By Associated Press.)\nAtlanta, Ga\u201e Feb. 25.\u2014The Supreme\nCourt of Georgia today refused to\ngrant a rehearing of the appeal for a\nnew trial of Iieo Frank, under death\nsentence for murdering fourteen-year\nold Mary Phagan. an employe in the\npencil factory of which he was super\nintendent.\n\n\n\nMisKlssippi\u2014Fair tonight and\nThursday g\n\n\nTHE WEATHER.\n\n\n\nFrom Bandit to General\nI\nI\ns.a\n\nX\n?\u00e4\nm\n<5\n\nThe News presents herewith the and today has all but ousted General\nvery first picture ever made of General Carranza as leader of the constitution-\nPancho Villa, of the Mexican Const!- allst army. He Is making a brave et- I\ntutionalists Army in his uniform, fort to conduct civilized warfare, but\nVilla is one of the most interesting j is said to be having a hard time keep\ncharacters in the revolution. Until j ing from reverting to outlaw methods,\nabout three years ago he was one of Not until the last few weeks has Villa\nthe most notorious bandits and out- worn a uniform, and it is understood\nlaws in Northern Mexico. He joined a handsome purse from the moving\nthe Madero forces in that revolution, picture men was all that induced him.\nAndersonW ould Reform\nState s Election Laws\nWANTS COUNTY TREASURIES INSTEAD OF THE PARTY EXEC\nUTIVE COMMITTEES TO DEFRAY EXPENSES\u2014ROTATION PLAN\nOF PLACING NAMES ON BALLOTS ALSO PROVIDED.\nis\n>ipecial to The News.\nJackson, Miss., Feb. 25.\u2014To Senator\nA. C. Anderson, president pro tempore\nof the senate, belongs the distinction\nof\nof framing more amendments to the\nelection laws of the state at this legis\nlative session than any member of\neither body.\nHe draf'ed the bill\npassed by both houses fixing the next\nsenatorial elections for 1916 and 1918,\nand also the measure fixing the third\nTuesday in August of alternate years\nfor congressional primaries.\nof\nSenator Anderson's latest proposed\nreform for the election laws is a bill\nproviding that hereafter the expense\nof printing tickets and holding pri\nmary elections shall be paid from the\ncounty treasury. Heretofore the vari\nous candidates have been assessed by\nthe party executive committees to de\nfray this expense, and often It is a\nvery heavy burden on the candidates.\nTo make a campaign for office in\nMississippi, especially a state office,\nis a very expensive proposition, often\n8\n\n\nHOUSE DENOUNCES\nH. A. WHITMAN\n\nMORRISON OF GRENADA SAY 8 HE\nOUGHT TO BE DRUMMED\nOUT OF 8 TATE.\nSpecial to The News.\nJackson, Miss., Feb. 25.\u2014The lower\nhouse this afternoon adopted a resolu\ntion offered by Mr. Walker of Lauder\ndale county, severely criticising Chan\ncellor H. A. Whitman, Jr., and de\nnouncing his official conduct for al\nlowing an excessive fee to receivers\nof the defunct bank at Meridian, and\nalao for hie action In taking a child\naway from her mother by judlfcial de\ncree.\nto\na\nDuring the debate Mr. Morrison of J\nGrenada declared that if it is true\nj that Chancellor Whitman took a ten- j\nmonths-old bahy from her mother's\ng arms, he ought to be kicked out of the I\nstate. I\namounting to more than the first\nyear's salary of the successful aspir\nant. Senator Anderson believes that\nthe county should bear this expense,\nand that it will be entirely legal to\nmake this provision.\nAnother provision of Senator Ander\nson's bill is that hereafter the names\nof candidates shall be placed on tick\nets in a rotation or alternate plan, so\nthat the name of no candidate shall\nlead the list oftener than that of any\nother candidate,\nthere are three candidates for Gover\nFor instance, if\nnor, and a county has 3,000 registered\nvoters, the name of each candidate\nshall appear first on one thousand of\nthe ballots printed.\nThis is a matter of considerable im\nportance. especially to aspirants for\nthe minor state offices,\naverage voter who knows nothing\nwhatever about the qualifications of\neither aspirant, and virtually has no\nchoice, will put the cross-mark op\nposite the first name he finds on the\nticket\nOften the\n\n9449999999M9999\nJAME8 J. HILL BAYS\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK GOOD.\n\nP\n\n\n\n(By Associated Press.)\nWashington. Feb. 25.\u2014James\nJ. Hill, veteran railroad builder\nof the northwest, talked with\nPresident Wilson today and said\nthe general business outlook in\nhis opinion is good.\n9999999999999999\nWill BEGIN WORK ON\nNEW BOMB N.0..M.&C.\nLauTel, Mias., Feb. 26.\u2014A rumor la\nin circulation here that work will be\nBtarted in a few days upon actual con\nstruction of the New Orleans line of\nthe New Orleans, Mobile A Chicago\nrailroad, to be constructed from Beau\nJ mont to Ansley. The survey of the Une\nwas completed some time ago, It\nj is said on good authority that Pree\nident Owens has completed the flnan\nI ciering of the contemplated improve\nI ments.\n\nAmerican nom\n1\nMAY BE SENT INTO\nMEXICAN CAMP\nTHIS GOVERNMENT DETERMINED\nTO RECOVER BODY OF WIL\nT\nLIAM 8 BENTON.\n\nWILL NOT BE ACT IF VAI\nr\nWilaon D\u00e9clar\u00e9e Ne Government\nExists in Mexico, so Sending of\nTroops There Will Not be Interven\ntion\u2014Fresh Appeals to Villa.\ni; Y\nA \u00ee\n(By Associated Press.)\nSpecial Bulletin.\nLaredo, Tex, Feb. 25.\u2014Official\nconfirmation of the report that\nClemente Vergara, American cit\nizen, was hanged by Mexican f\u00f6d\nerale near Hidalgo, Mexico, has\njust been received. It Is reported\nthe body is still hanging, though it\nis believed the execution took\nplace February thirteenth or four\nteenth. Vergara was a ranchman\nin Texas and pastured horses on\nan island in the Rio Grande. On\nhis complaint that Mexicans were\nstealing his horses, Texas rang\u00e9es\nwere sent to protect hie property.\nMexicans appeared on the island\nFeb. thirteenth and called him to\ncome over. Against the advice of\nrangers he did oo. The Mexicans\nstruck him and carried him into\nMexico.\n\nI\nEl Paso, Tex., Feb. 25.\u2014Louis\nCabra re, Carranza's confidential\nsecretary, arrived last night and\nrushed on a special train to Chi\nhuahua to investigate the Benton\nkilling. Speaking of the Benton\nand Bauch cases he is reported ta\nhave said the rebels must dear\nup evidence no matter how black\nit might look for them.\nWashington, Feb. 25.\u2014Villa's\nproposal that Benton's body be\nexamined but not removed from\nMexican soil has been accepted by\nthe United States. Relatives, ac\ncompanied by army surgeons will\nview and examine the corpse.\nThis Governfent will\nclaims that the body should bo\nreturned to the United States, but\nhas accepted the other proposal\nso as to have an immediate exam\nination.\nSecretary Bryan discussed the\nMexican situation for two hours/\nwith the Foreign Relations com\nmittee of the Senate this after\nnoon, but nothing of importance\nwas announced.\nit*\n%A\n(By Associated Pr es s!\nWashington, Feb. 25.\u2014That a tore*\nof United States Cavalry will ba net\ninto Mexico to receive the body of\nWilliam S. Benton Beamed pro b a bl e\nhere today. Fresh representations to\nVilla to turn over the remains of the\nexecuted Englishman w\nday without requit, and the United\nStates, in Its effort to mate tain cer\ndlally friendly relations with\nland. Is becoming weary of the tne\ntics of Villa.\nThe sending of troops Into Mexico\nfor this purpose would net be an net\nof war.\ndared there 1 b no gover nm e nt In It\nico, so there la no government far\nthe United States to war\nGeneral Carran\nrive at Juarea at early an Wnfig\nand conduct an Inquiry into the ex\ntlou cX the Britlaher.\nImmediately upon receipt at\nfrom Chihuahua that the body of\nton would be exhumed, ae that rata\nPresident Wttaan has de\n\na\na representative of the United\nGovernment, a second request was\nsent asking Villa to deliver the body\nla\nof\nIt\non American aoiL\nFrom the character of the\ndiscovered on Benton's body, physt\nclaps will be able to any whether Baa\nton waa killed by a pistol ahnt, an\nfriend* claim, or by a firing\ntod to official circle\u00bb that\nination will be of grant vain\naffirming or disproving a*\npoint in Villa's general\nthe affair. i\n\nSr, Mi","height":"17400","width":"13968"}}
